    "summary": "Bad idea — the Chinese example IS the argument, not decoration",
    "content": "**Bad idea.** The 道德仁义礼 example is not an illustration of the author's argument -- it *is* the argument. The reversal (bottom-up construction disguised as top-down generation) is demonstrated *through* the specific structure of that sequence: the way 礼 generates 义 generates 仁 generates 德 generates 道, and then the whole thing is flipped. A Western substitute would have to be an entirely different argument, not just a different example of the same argument.\n\nThe translation difficulty is real but bounded. It is one passage in one essay, with five terms that each need one gloss at first occurrence. After that, the English carries itself: \"Dao generates character, human character is humaneness, from humaneness arises rightness, from rightness comes ritual conduct.\" That sentence is perfectly readable. The apparatus is front-loaded and then disappears.\n\nRemoving the Chinese example would also strip the work of its most distinctive feature: a philosopher working *from within* the Chinese tradition to make a structurally original point about how metaphysical hierarchies are constructed. That is precisely what makes 境集 interesting to an English-language audience."
  }
